Even now too they were still legally incapable of possessing the ager publicus ; and this ap- peared the more hard, because, on the one hand, their taxation was out of all proportion to that oi the patricians, while the possession os the ager publicus was untaxed, and yet, on the other, it was mainly through their own valour that it had become ager publicus at all. Some slight compensation was made lor this by alex Cassia (ac. 486) which effected a distribution of newly-conquered territory, and placed some restrictions on the patrician enjoyment of the public land. A third grievance was the unlimited power ol the magistrates to inflict pecuniary fines ς’ this was curtailed hythe leges Menenia, Tarpeia, and Papiria, passed between 460 and 430 nc. Lastly, the patriciana controlled the entire administration ol justice ; it was the consul who presided over the preliminary stage ol every aetion, and it he did not decide it out of hand, the judges were most usually the patrician decemviri, upon whom this function had been cast by Servius Tullius, it was the pontifices themselves, members ol the patrician caste, who interpreted the law, and solved its knotty prob- lems. Moreover, the very enforcement ol the law depended on the observance ol minute forms and technicalities of which, by reason ol their implication with the ius sacrum, the plebeian could know little or nothing. Some slight amelioration ol these hard conditione must have been adorded by the lex Pinaria ¹, which belongs to this period, and which, in certain classes ol actions (we may suppose, in particular, actions ol debt), allowed the parties to choose a single judge, to the exclusion ol the magistrates' own jurisdiction and ol the decemviral court (Gaius iv. 15). But the class from which the judge was to be chosen seems to have been limited iu some way ot' which we have no certain knowledge; and the chief interest ol the lex Pinaria is that it served as a precedent lor the principle enunciated by Cicero (pro Cluentio 43) in the words ‘neminem voluerunt maiores nostri esse iudicem nisi qui inter adversarios convenisset?
